<br>
/em looks forward to having all three movies on DVD someday so he can sit back at the house having drinks and stuff and watch all three movies back to back. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uakomofcazicthule.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Akom of Cazic Thule</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Been around a while</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(12/23/01 10:58:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1447.topic&index=32>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://sanguinecrusaders.homestead.com/files/Akom_Jump.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: ...</span><hr size=1> Star Wars Universe > LotR Universe.<br>
<br>
But can you really compare the two?  They are what you compare other movies / books to to see how good they are.  Star Wars was an awesome movie.  Do I think LotR was better  visually?  Yes.  After all... compare the budgets of the first star wars movies and LotR.  They can afford to go all out.  Also the technology that is availiable now is FAR better than what was around at the makeing of Star Wars.  Yet, star wars is an AWESOME trilogy.  It didn't have any books that it had to stick to, or any fans to worry about upsetting.<br>
<br>
They had to cut a LOT of things from LotR in order to make it under 3 hrs (we see VERY few movies over 3 hours now days).  This, unfortunatly, made the first half of the movie seem too fast (didn't go by too fast... things happened too fast), I.e.: Almost ALL of the traveling was instantaineous.  It didn't give the feel that they were on a long epic journey.  The cheery times that Tolkien put in in between the dark parts of the journey were almost compleatly cut from the movie.  No singing, no light spirits...  the movie centered on the darker side of the book.  <br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, I loved LotR, however there are some major flaws in it.  Yes, the movie was awesome for someone who has read the books, but not everyone has.  Now you may be thinking, "pfft, how many people havn't read Lord of the Rings?"... I was suprised to find out that a good number of my friends hadn't.  A major flaw in the movie is the failure to explain some things.  Like that the Ring Wraiths were afraid of water and fire (and why they were). <br>
<br>
If you look at Lord of the Rings as a new idea and a new movie by itself, it is awesome.  However, since it was based on (in my opinion) the best fantasy book of all time, it could very well have been the best movie of all time, however with the small noticable flaws and the small plot changes, it loses some of it's glory.<br>
<br>
Taken Movie for movie... LotR is better than A New Hope.  But if you look at the background, the history, the universe that has grown from star wars, and compare it to that of LotR, star wars is the superior.  They say LotR is the forfather of fantasy.  Maybe it is, but thats the book.  We're discussing movies.  If Star Wars was spawned from a book, then maybe we'd have a comparison.<br>
<br>
If any of this dosn't make sense, check back later.  Its 2 am now and I'm tired (just got back from a long drive).  Gonna come back tomorrow and read this post to make sure it is conveying my thoughts correctly.<br>
<br>
Night.    <br>
